default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default4.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposals to eliminate requirements for provision of cycle storage sit awkwardly with the Government’s clear commitment to encouraging more cycling. In responding to the All Party Parliamentary Cycling Group report 
defaultGet Britain Cycling 
default(2013)
default, 
defaultTransport Minister Norman Baker said:
default&#xa0;
default “The coalition government takes cycling very seriously and we are committed to leading the country in getting more people cycling, more safely, more often”
default&#xa0;
default4.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultStorage is one of the practical barriers to further growth in cycling and we believe building regulations should support provision of secure cycle storage for each new home with the potential of local variation according to current and future demand.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default5.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposals seem a sensible approach.  We support the ability of and the capability for local authorities to impose a tighter minimum standard in areas of water scarcity although an alternative approach would be to establisher higher 
defaulteffeiciency
default standards and allow these to be relaxed in areas of relative water surplus.
default&#xa0;
default5.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposal for a specification checklist of compliant flow rates for each fitting is very welcome.  It offers increased transparency and an outcomes based framework for builders which will allow for innovation and different approaches.  We believe the specification list could be improved in a number of areas:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default6.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSustainable Homes welcome the inclusion of space standards in the consultation. These are currently unregulated through building regulations but assessed through HQIs. 
default&#xa0;
default6.1.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe two options of a minimum space standard or a space labelling scheme are presented as mutually exclusive.  We support a hybrid approach which establishes minimum standards in building regulations across all tenures and then uses a space labelling scheme.  This will help prospective residents make informed decisions in choosing new homes which have larger rooms
default.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default7.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposals on waste and recycling storage provision are confused and inconsistent.  There is welcome provision to 
defaultto
default strengthen requirements for external recycling space but too little attention to the implications of how recycling will be accommodated internall
defaulty.
default Internal recycling bins are mentioned in the design element of proposals for minimum space standards but not addressed in the proposals for space labelling. 
default&#xa0;
default7.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultA study by WRAP (2008) found that a lack of internal space for recycling is a significant barrier to household recycling.  
defaultI
defaultnternal installation of space for recycling should be required under all options.
default&#xa0;
default7.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSpace for internal recycling storage should be required in building regulations.
default&#xa0;default8.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultSustainable Homes is seriously concerned 
defaultby
default the failure of the consultation document and the accompanying impact assessment to take account of the value accruing from broader sustainability and management considerations in housing standards.  These protect and contribute to wider environmental, social and health outcomes. This is a serious omission. 
default8.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe following important considerations are currently included in standards but are omitted from the consultation: 
default8.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThere is no indication of how these benefits are to be provided under the new arrangements.  Sustainable Homes has received responses from approximately 200 housing professionals on their views on whether materials, waste and other 
defaultenvironmental issues should be regulated in housing.
default&#xa0;
default Around 75% of those asked stated that they believe they should be regulated
default (Sustainable Homes, 2013)
default.
default&#xa0;
default8.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe 
defaultfocus
default here on outlining practical ways that materials and ecology may be brought into a revised regulatory system.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default9.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThere may be a case for simplifying how responsible sourcing is demonstrated but omitting it altogether does not seem to be a reasonable response.  The consultation suggests that existing voluntary industry standards cover these areas and that regulation is therefore unnecessary. We do not agree. The voluntary standards mentioned in the consultation, including BS, ISO and CE, govern aspects of quality, design and processes but they do not cover the issues of embodied energy and environmental impacts of materials.
default&#xa0;
default9.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposals put at risk the key benefits from responsible sourcing – using materials which do not require human exploitation and encouraging greater use of recycled materials and reduced landfill.  The 
defaultuPVC
default is one area where the benefits of greater recycling are evident and there is significant potential in growing this part of the green economy.   
default&#xa0;
default9.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe suggest three policy options to encourage the use of more sustainable materials
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default10.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEcology is simply ignored in the consultation document.  This gross omission reinforces concerns raised by the Government’s Natural Capital Committee, that policies are too often based on economic rationalisation without reference to the value of our natural assets (2013). Ecological management in development processes are an important part of reversing a trend of biodiversity loss: populations of farmland and woodland species have declined by 28% and 17% respectively since 1990 (DEFRA, 2009). 
default&#xa0;
default10.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBiodiversity is crucial for a healthy ecosystem, upon which humans depend and it has important social and economic value.
default&#xa0;
default The Government’s Natural Environment White Paper is unequivocal in recognising that:
default&#xa0;
default“
defaultNature is sometimes taken for granted and undervalued. But people cannot flourish without the benefits and services our natural environment provides. Nature is a complex, interconnected system. A healthy, properly functioning natural environment is the foundation of sustained economic growth, prospering communities and personal wellbeing.
defaultThis is why we must properly value the economic and social benefits of a healthy natural environment while continuing to recognise nature’s intrinsic value. The Government wants this to be the first generation to leave the natural environment of England in a better state than it inherited. To achieve so much means taking action across sectors rather than treating environmental concerns in isolation. It requires us all to put the value of nature at the heart of our decision-making – in Government, local communities and businesses. In this way we will improve the quality and increase the value of the natural environment across England.
default”
default&#xa0;
default10.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBy omitting consideration of ecology the Housing Standards Review risks being an unfortunate example of taking nature for granted.
default&#xa0;
default10.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHousing development has a major impact on biodiversity.  As well as damaging and fragmenting existing habitats and ecosystems new development creates different opportunities for supporting wildlife.  The nation’s gardens are one of its most important wildlife resources and residents also benefit – whether through contact with nature in their back garden or the additional cooling effect of vegetation during increasingly extreme heat wave events.  
defaultE
defaultnvironmental 
defaultbenefits of biodiversity
default 
defaulthave been estimated as valued in the 
defaultbillions in health impacts alone
default 
default(
defaultUK National Ecosystem Assessment
default, 2011)
default. 
default&#xa0;
default10.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe suggest two policy options to encourage address biodiversity in new housing:
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default11.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe support the focus on building control officers and approved bodies to implement the standards.  This will be a significantly expanded and more complex role and we have concerns about the capacity and expertise within current building control teams to deliver.
default&#xa0;
default11.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe believe the new approach to housing standards needs to be accompanied by a significant boost in the competency and status of the building control profession.  This needs to embrace sustainability as an important area for development.  Sustainability is a relatively new field with a wide variety of unregulated information from products and suppliers and this presents a challenge to building control departments.  We believe 
defaultthere is a need for an extra accredited qualification for building control officers who will be approving the sustainability elements of building regulations as part of the review.
